Boil a large #pot{} of salted water for the @egg noodles{150%grams}.

When the water is boiling, add the noodles and bring back to the boil.

Cook until softened, ~{4-6%mins}.

Drain in a #sieve{} and return to the pot, off the heat.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and toss to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Trim the @green beans{75%grams} and chop into thirds.

Roughly chop the @mushrooms{150%grams}.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2%units} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%grams}(chopped) (stalks and all).

Quarter the @lemon{1%unit}.

Place a large #pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.

Once hot, add the @diced Irish chicken breast{260%grams} and mushrooms.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Fry until chicken is golden on the outside and cooked through, ~{6-8%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Add the green beans and fry for ~{4-5%mins}.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal due to packaging we use to keep it fresh.

Add the @curry powder{1%sachet} and garlic and fry until fragrant, ~{1%min}.

> IMPORTANT: Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Remove the pan from the heat and stir in the @miso paste{1%sachet} and @ketjap manis{2%sachets}.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if the sauce is too thick.

Add the drained noodles to the pan and stir to coat.

Add a squeeze of lemon juice.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Divide the noodles between #bowls{}.

Top with the @peanuts{20%grams} and chopped coriander.

Serve remaining lemon wedges alongside.